 // Output data of each row while(row = result->fetch_assoc()) { echo \\"<tr><td>\\" . row\\"id\\". \\"</td><td>\\" . row\\"first_name\\". \\"</td><td>\\" . row\\"last_name\\". \\"</td><td>\\" . row\\"age\\". \\"</td></tr>\\"; } echo \\"</table>\\"; } else { echo \\"0 results\\"; } conn->close(); ?> </body> </html>, <?php servername = \\"your_servername\\"; username = \\"your_username\\"; password = \\"your_password\\"; dbname = \\"your_dbname\\"; // Create connection conn = new mysqli(servername, username, password, dbname); // Check connection if (conn->connect_error) { die(\\"Connection failed: \\" . conn->connect_error); } sql = \\"SELECT * FROM users WHERE age BETWEEN 18 AND 25 ORDER BY last_name ASC\\"; result = conn->query(sql); if (result->num_rows > 0) { echo \\"<table><tr><th>ID</th><th>First Name</th><th>Last Name</th><th>Age</th></tr>\\"; // Output data of each row while(row = result->fetch_assoc()) { echo \\"<tr><td>\\" . row\\"id\\". \\"</td><td>\\" . row\\"first_name\\". \\"</td><td>\\" . row\\"last_name\\". \\"</td><td>\\" . row\\"age\\". \\"</td></tr>\\"; } echo \\"</table>\\"; } else { echo \\"0 results\\"; } conn->close(); ?>"},{"prompt":"How many times does Earth orbit the Sun in 1000 years?","candidates_completions":"The Earth orbits the Sun once every 365.25 days, which accounts for leap years. To find out how many times the Earth orbits the Sun in 1000 years, we need to multiply the number of years by the number of orbits per year. We'll use the decimal form (365.25 days) to account for leap years more accurately: Number of orbits = Years * Orbits per year = 1000 * 1 = 1000 So, the Earth orbits the Sun approximately 1000 times in 1000 years.,Earth orbits the Sun approximately once every 365.25 days, not including leap years. To calculate how many times Earth orbits the Sun in 1000 years, convert the decimal to the nearest whole number. This is: (365.25 days/year) Ã— 1000 years = 365,250 days As there are 365.25 days in a year, Earth orbits the Sun around 365 times within 1000 years.,The Earth orbits the Sun once every 365.25 days, which accounts for leap years. To find out how many times the Earth orbits the Sun in 1000 years, we simply multiply the number of years by the number of orbits per year: Number of orbits = Years * Orbits per year = 1000 * 1 = 1000 So, the Earth orbits the Sun approximately 1000 times in 1000 years."},{"prompt":"A farmer has 50 acres of land on which he plants corn and wheat. He allocates 60% of the land for corn and the rest for wheat. If each acre of corn yields 120 bushels and each acre of wheat yields 80 bushels, what is the total yield in bushels from both crops?","candidates_completions":"First, let's find out how many acres are allocated for each crop: Acres of corn = Total acres * Percentage of land for corn = 50 * 0.6 = 30 acres Acres of wheat = Total acres - Acres of corn = 50 - 30 = 20 acres Next, we'll calculate the yield in bushels for each crop: Bushels of corn = Acres of corn * Yield per acre of corn = 30 * 120 = 3,600 bushels Bushels of wheat = Acres of wheat * Yield per acre of wheat = 20 * 80 = 1,600 bushels Finally, we'll add the yields from both crops to find the total yield: Total yield = Bushels of corn + Bushels of wheat = 3,600 + 1,600 = 5,200 bushels So, the total yield from both crops is 5,200 bushels.,To find the total yield in bushels from both crops, first we need to determine how many acres are used for each crop. The farmer allocates 60% of the land for corn, so 40% of the land is used for wheat. First, find the percentage of land used for each crop: Corn: 50 acres * 0.60 = 30 acres Wheat: 50 acres * 0.40 = 20 acres Next, we calculate the yield for each crop per acre and multiply it by the number of acres for each crop: Corn yield = 30 acres * 120 bushels/acre = 3600 bushels Wheat yield = 20 acres * 80 bushels/acre = 1600 bushels Now, add up the yields for both crops to find the total yield: Total yield = Corn yield + Wheat yield = 3600 bushels + 